Rating: 2
I'd make this again, but only with significant changes. First, this produces a heavy, gluey, gravy-like sauce, not the light, lemony sauce which usually characterizes this dish. Next time I'd leave out the flour, except for dredging the chicken breast in. Secondly, 2 tblsp. of oil doesn't do it--you'll need at least 3. Thirdly, in order to avoid a sauce that tastes overpoweringly of lemon, you'll have to double the amount of chicken stock called for and use a couple of more tablespoons of wine. The best way to produce a great piccata sauce is to deglaze the pan first with the wine, scraping up all the delectable brown bits and stirring until the wine is somewhat reduced and the liquid begins to thicken. Next add the lemon juice and chicken stock and bring to a low boil, stirring constantly. Finally, remove the pan from the heat, stir in the butter to finish the sauce, and add the capers and parsley.

